accessibleThroughQuery/comment:
partially as we can run only some query examples. The query SELECT * WHERE {
  ?s ?p ?o
} LIMIT 100
can be executed, however it seems that the only predicate the dataset uses is http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#rest 

For each consecutive and overlapping pair of events (n, o) in s, the following statement is added to the graph:

n.string-value <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#rest> o.string-value .

In this case I think we can consider it as working and available.

The query SELECT * WHERE {
  ?s ?p ?o
} LIMIT 100
can be executed, however it seems that the only predicate the dataset uses is http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#rest which's semantics is that

For each consecutive and overlapping pair of events (n, o) in s, the following statement is added to the graph:

n.string-value <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#rest> o.string-value .

In this case I think we can consider it as working and available. 

However, this dataset and the following have the same sparql endpoint and the same dataset link. I gues we can consider them as one?
